[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This, like the Fibonacci-numbers example, is horribly slow because it too exhibits the **overlapping sub-problems** attribute.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] That is, it recomputes the same path costs over and over.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] However, we can compute it much faster in a bottom-up fashion if we store path costs in a two-dimensional array `q[i, j]` rather than using a function.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This avoids recomputation; all the values needed for array `q[i, j]` are computed ahead of time only once.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Precomputed values for `(i,j)` are simply looked up whenever needed.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] We also need to know what the actual shortest path is.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] To do this, we use another array `p[i, j]`; a *predecessor array*.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This array records the path to any square `s`.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The predecessor of `s` is modeled as an offset relative to the index (in `q[i, j]`) of the precomputed path cost of `s`.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] To reconstruct the complete path, we lookup the predecessor of `s`, then the predecessor of that square, then the predecessor of that square, and so on recursively, until we reach the starting square.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Now the rest is a simple matter of finding the minimum and printing it.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] In genetics, sequence alignment is an important application where dynamic programming is essential.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Typically, the problem consists of transforming one sequence into another using edit operations that replace, insert, or remove an element.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Each operation has an associated cost, and the goal is to find the sequence of edits with the lowest total cost.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] 3. replacing the first character of A with the first character of B, and performing optimal alignments of the tails of A and B.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The partial alignments can be tabulated in a matrix, where cell (i,j) contains the cost of the optimal alignment of A[1..i] to B[1..j].
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The cost in cell (i,j) can be calculated by adding the cost of the relevant operations to the cost of its neighboring cells, and selecting the optimum.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Different variants exist, see Smith–Waterman algorithm and Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The **Tower of Hanoi** or **Towers of Hanoi** is a mathematical game or puzzle.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] S(n, h, t) := solution to a problem consisting of n disks that are to be moved from rod h to rod t.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] For n=1 the problem is trivial, namely S(1,h,t) = "move a disk from rod h to rod t" (there is only one disk left).
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The number of moves required by this solution is 2*n* − 1.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] If the objective is to **maximize** the number of moves (without cycling) then the dynamic programming functional equation is slightly more complicated and 3*n* − 1 moves are required.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] A famous puzzle relates to dropping eggs from a building to determine at which height they start to break.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] terminology, in which the first floor is at ground level).
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] If only one egg is available and we wish to be sure of obtaining the right result, the experiment can be carried out in only one way.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Drop the egg from the first-floor window; if it survives, drop it from the second-floor window.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] In the worst case, this method may require 36 droppings.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] What is the lowest number of egg-droppings that is guaranteed to work in all cases?
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] For instance, *s* = (2,6) indicates that two test eggs are available and 6 (consecutive) floors are yet to be tested.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The initial state of the process is *s* = (*N*,*H*) where *N* denotes the number of test eggs available at the commencement of the experiment.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The process terminates either when there are no more test eggs (*n* = 0) or when *k* = 0, whichever occurs first.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] If termination occurs at state *s* = (0,*k*) and *k* > 0, then the test failed.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] It is easy to solve this equation iteratively by systematically increasing the values of *n* and *k*.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Notice that the above solution takes $O(nk^{2})$ time with a DP solution.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This can be improved to $O(nk\log k)$ time by binary searching on the optimal x in the above recurrence, since $W(n-1,x-1)$ is increasing in x while $W(n,k-x)$ is decreasing in x , thus a local minimum of $\max(W(n-1,x-1),W(n,k-x))$ is a global minimum.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Also, by storing the optimal x for each cell in the DP table and referring to its value for the previous cell, the optimal x for each cell can be found in constant time, improving it to $O(nk)$ time.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Let k be the total number of floors such that the eggs break when dropped from the k th floor (The example above is equivalent to taking $k=37$ ).
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Let m be the minimum floor from which the egg must be dropped to be broken.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Let $f(t,n)$ be the maximum number of values of m that are distinguishable using t tries and n eggs.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Let a be the floor from which the first egg is dropped in the optimal strategy.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] If the first egg broke, m is from 1 to a and distinguishable using at most $t-1$ tries and $n-1$ eggs.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] If the first egg did not break, m is from $a+1$ to k and distinguishable using $t-1$ tries and n eggs.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Then the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum x such that $f(x,n)\geq k$ .
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] To do so, we could compute $\{f(t,i):0\leq i\leq n\}$ in order of increasing t , which would take $O(nx)$ time.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Thus, if we separately handle the case of $n=1$ , the algorithm would take $O(n{\sqrt {k}})$ time.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] But the recurrence relation can in fact be solved, giving $f(t,n)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}{\binom {t}{i}}$ , which can be computed in $O(n)$ time using the identity ${\binom {t}{i+1}}={\binom {t}{i}}{\frac {t-i}{i+1}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Since $f(t,n)\leq f(t+1,n)$ for all $t\geq 0$ , we can binary search on t to find x , giving an $O(n\log k)$ algorithm.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:operations-research/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] An **integer programming**, also known as **integer optimization**, problem is a mathematical optimization or feasibility program in which some or all of the variables are restricted to be integers.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In many settings the term refers to **integer linear programming** (ILP), in which the objective function and the constraints (other than the integer constraints) are linear.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Integer programming is NP-complete (the difficult part is showing the NP membership).
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In particular, the special case of 0–1 integer linear programming, in which unknowns are binary, and only the restrictions must be satisfied, is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] If some decision variables are not discrete, the problem is known as a **mixed-integer programming** problem.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Integer linear programs can be expressed either in *canonical form* or *standard form* (both as defined below), which are different from each other.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] where $\mathbf {c} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n},\mathbf {b} \in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ are vectors and $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ is a matrix.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] As with linear programs, ILPs not in standard form can be converted to standard form by eliminating inequalities, introducing slack variables ( $\mathbf {s}$ ) and replacing variables that are not sign-constrained with the difference of two sign-constrained variables.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The plot on the right shows the following problem.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The feasible integer points are shown in red, and the red dashed lines indicate their convex hull, which is the smallest convex polyhedron that contains all of these points.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The blue lines together with the coordinate axes define the polyhedron of the LP relaxation, which is given by the inequalities without the integrality constraint.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The goal of the optimization is to move the black dashed line as far upward while still touching the polyhedron.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The optimal solutions of the integer problem are the points $(1,2)$ and $(2,2)$ that both have an objective value of 2.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The unique optimum of the relaxation is $(1.8,2.8)$ with objective value of 2.8.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] If the solution of the relaxation is rounded to the nearest integers, it is not feasible for the ILP.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The following is a reduction from minimum vertex cover to integer programming that will serve as the proof of NP-hardness.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Any feasible solution to the integer program will be nonzero on a subset of vertices.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The first constraint implies that at least one end point of every edge is included in this subset.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Therefore, the solution describes a vertex cover.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Additionally given some vertex cover C, $y_{v}$ can be set to 1 for any $v\in C$ and to 0 for any $v\not \in C$ thus giving us a feasible solution to the integer program.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Thus we can conclude that if we minimize the sum of $y_{v}$ we have also found the minimum vertex cover.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Other integer variables represent decisions (e.g. whether to include an edge in a graph) and so should only take on the value 0 or 1.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] These considerations occur frequently in practice and so integer linear programming can be used in many applications areas, some of which are briefly described below.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Mixed-integer programming has many applications in industrial productions, including job-shop modelling.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] One important example happens in agricultural production planning and involves determining production yield for several crops that can share resources (e.g. land, labor, capital, seeds, fertilizer, etc.).
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] A possible objective is to maximize the total production, without exceeding the available resources.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In some cases, this can be expressed in terms of a linear program, but the variables must be constrained to be integer.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] These problems involve service and vehicle scheduling in transportation networks.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] For example, a problem may involve assigning buses or subways to individual routes so that a timetable can be met, and also to equip them with drivers.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Here binary decision variables indicate whether a bus or subway is assigned to a route and whether a driver is assigned to a particular train or subway.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The zero–one programming technique has been successfully applied to solve a project selection problem in which projects are mutually exclusive and/or technologically interdependent.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Territorial partitioning or districting problems consist of partitioning a geographical region into districts in order to plan some operations while considering different criteria or constraints.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Some requirements for this problem are: contiguity, compactness, balance or equity, respect of natural boundaries, and socio-economic homogeneity.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Some applications for this type of problem include: political districting, school districting, health services districting and waste management districting.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The goal of these problems is to design a network of lines to install so that a predefined set of communication requirements are met and the total cost of the network is minimal.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] This requires optimizing both the topology of the network along with setting the capacities of the various lines.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In many cases, the capacities are constrained to be integer quantities.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Usually there are, depending on the technology used, additional restrictions that can be modeled as linear inequalities with integer or binary variables.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The task of frequency planning in GSM mobile networks involves distributing available frequencies across the antennas so that users can be served and interference is minimized between the antennas.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] This problem can be formulated as an integer linear program in which binary variables indicate whether a frequency is assigned to an antenna.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The naive way to solve an ILP is to simply remove the constraint that **x** is integer, solve the corresponding LP (called the LP relaxation of the ILP), and then round the entries of the solution to the LP relaxation.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] But, not only may this solution not be optimal, it may not even be feasible; that is, it may violate some constraint.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Consequently, the solution returned by the simplex algorithm is guaranteed to be integral.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] To show that every basic feasible solution is integral, let $\mathbf {x}$ be an arbitrary basic feasible solution .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Since $\mathbf {x}$ is feasible, we know that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Let $\mathbf {x} _{0}=[x_{n_{1}},x_{n_{2}},\cdots ,x_{n_{j}}]$ be the elements corresponding to the basis columns for the basic solution $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] By definition of a basis, there is some square submatrix B of A with linearly independent columns such that $B\mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Since the columns of B are linearly independent and B is square, B is nonsingular, and therefore by assumption, B is unimodular and so $\det(B)=\pm 1$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Also, since B is nonsingular, it is invertible and therefore $\mathbf {x} _{0}=B^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Here $B^{\mathrm {adj} }$ denotes the adjugate of B and is integral because B is integral.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] When the matrix A is not totally unimodular, there are a variety of algorithms that can be used to solve integer linear programs exactly.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] One class of algorithms are cutting plane methods, which work by solving the LP relaxation and then adding linear constraints that drive the solution towards being integer without excluding any integer feasible points.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Another class of algorithms are variants of the branch and bound method.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] For example, the branch and cut method that combines both branch and bound and cutting plane methods.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Branch and bound algorithms have a number of advantages over algorithms that only use cutting planes.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] One advantage is that the algorithms can be terminated early and as long as at least one integral solution has been found, a feasible, although not necessarily optimal, solution can be returned.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Further, the solutions of the LP relaxations can be used to provide a worst-case estimate of how far from optimality the returned solution is.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Finally, branch and bound methods can be used to return multiple optimal solutions.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Suppose A is an *m*-by-*n* integer matrix and $\mathbf {b}$ is an *m*-by-1 integer vector.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] We focus on the feasibility problem, which is to decide whether there exists an *n*-by-1 vector $\mathbf {x}$ satisfying $A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Let *V* be the maximum absolute value of the coefficients in A and $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] If *n* (the number of variables) is a fixed constant, then the feasibility problem can be solved in time polynomial in *m* and log *V*.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The case *n*=2 was solved in 1981 by Herbert Scarf.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The general case was solved in 1983 by Hendrik Lenstra, combining ideas by László Lovász and Peter van Emde Boas.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In the special case of 0-1 ILP, Lenstra's algorithm is equivalent to complete enumeration: the number of all possible solutions is fixed (2*n*), and checking the feasibility of each solution can be done in time poly(*m*, log *V*).
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In the general case, where each variable can be an arbitrary integer, complete enumeration is impossible.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Here, Lenstra's algorithm uses ideas from Geometry of numbers.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] It transforms the original problem into an equivalent one with the following property: either the existence of a solution $\mathbf {x}$ is obvious, or the value of $x_{n}$ (the *n*-th variable) belongs to an interval whose length is bounded by a function of *n*.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In the latter case, the problem is reduced to a bounded number of lower-dimensional problems.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] These algorithms can also be used for **mixed integer linear programs** (MILP) - programs in which some variables are integer and some variables are real.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The original algorithm of Lenstra has run-time $2^{O(n^{3})}\cdot poly(d,L)$ , where n is the number of integer variables, d is the number of continuous variables, and *L* is the binary encoding size of the problem.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Using techniques from later algorithms, the factor $2^{O(n^{3})}$ can be improved to $2^{O(n\log n)}$ or to $n^{n}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Since integer linear programming is NP-hard, many problem instances are intractable and so heuristic methods must be used instead.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] For example, tabu search can be used to search for solutions to ILPs.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] To use tabu search to solve ILPs, moves can be defined as incrementing or decrementing an integer constrained variable of a feasible solution while keeping all other integer-constrained variables constant.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The unrestricted variables are then solved for.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Short-term memory can consist of previously tried solutions while medium-term memory can consist of values for the integer constrained variables that have resulted in high objective values (assuming the ILP is a maximization problem).
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Finally, long-term memory can guide the search towards integer values that have not previously been tried.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] There are also a variety of other problem-specific heuristics, such as the k-opt heuristic for the traveling salesman problem.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] A disadvantage of heuristic methods is that if they fail to find a solution, it cannot be determined whether it is because there is no feasible solution or whether the algorithm simply was unable to find one.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Further, it is usually impossible to quantify how close to optimal a solution returned by these methods are.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] It is often the case that the matrix A that defines the integer program is *sparse*.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In particular, this occurs when the matrix has a block structure, which is the case in many applications.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The sparsity of the matrix can be measured as follows.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The *graph* of A has vertices corresponding to columns of A , and two columns form an edge if A has a row where both columns have nonzero entries.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Equivalently, the vertices correspond to variables, and two variables form an edge if they share an inequality.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] The *sparsity measure* d of A is the minimum of the tree-depth of the graph of A and the tree-depth of the graph of the transpose of A .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Let a be the *numeric measure* of A defined as the maximum absolute value of any entry of A .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Let n be the number of variables of the integer program.
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Then it was shown in 2018 that integer programming can be solved in strongly polynomial and fixed-parameter tractable time parameterized by a and d .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] That is, for some computable function f and some constant k , integer programming can be solved in time $f(a,d)n^{k}$ .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] In particular, the time is independent of the right-hand side b and objective function c .
[src:operations-research/integer-programming] Moreover, in contrast to the classical result of Lenstra, where the number n of variables is a parameter, here the number n of variables is a variable part of the input.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] More formally, linear programming is a technique for the optimization of a linear objective function, subject to linear equality and linear inequality constraints.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Its feasible region is a convex polytope, which is a set defined as the intersection of finitely many half spaces, each of which is defined by a linear inequality.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Its objective function is a real-valued affine (linear) function defined on this polytope.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] A linear programming algorithm finds a point in the polytope where this function has the largest (or smallest) value if such a point exists.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Here the components of $\mathbf {x}$ are the variables to be determined, $\mathbf {c}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ are given vectors, and A is a given matrix.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The function whose value is to be maximized ( $\mathbf {x} \mapsto \mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x}$ in this case) is called the objective function.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The constraints $A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b}$ and $\mathbf {x} \geq \mathbf {0}$ specify a convex polytope over which the objective function is to be optimized.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Linear programming can be applied to various fields of study.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] It is widely used in mathematics and, to a lesser extent, in business, economics, and some engineering problems.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] There is a close connection between linear programs, eigenequations, John von Neumann's general equilibrium model, and structural equilibrium models (see dual linear program for details).
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Industries that use linear programming models include transportation, energy, telecommunications, and manufacturing.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] It has proven useful in modeling diverse types of problems in planning, routing, scheduling, assignment, and design.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The problem of solving a system of linear inequalities dates back at least as far as Fourier, who in 1827 published a method for solving them, and after whom the method of Fourier–Motzkin elimination is named.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In the late 1930s, Soviet mathematician Leonid Kantorovich and American economist Wassily Leontief independently delved into the practical applications of linear programming.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Kantorovich focused on manufacturing schedules, while Leontief explored economic applications.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Their groundbreaking work was largely overlooked for decades.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The turning point came during World War II when linear programming emerged as a vital tool.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] It found extensive use in addressing complex wartime challenges, including transportation logistics, scheduling, and resource allocation.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Linear programming proved invaluable in optimizing these processes while considering critical constraints such as costs and resource availability.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Despite its initial obscurity, the wartime successes propelled linear programming into the spotlight.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Post-WWII, the method gained widespread recognition and became a cornerstone in various fields, from operations research to economics.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The overlooked contributions of Kantorovich and Leontief in the late 1930s eventually became foundational to the broader acceptance and utilization of linear programming in optimizing decision-making processes.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Kantorovich's work was initially neglected in the USSR.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] About the same time as Kantorovich, the Dutch-American economist T.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Koopmans formulated classical economic problems as linear programs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Kantorovich and Koopmans later shared the 1975 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In 1941, Frank Lauren Hitchcock also formulated transportation problems as linear programs and gave a solution very similar to the later simplex method.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Hitchcock had died in 1957, and the Nobel Memorial Prize is not awarded posthumously.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Dantzig independently developed general linear programming formulation to use for planning problems in the US Air Force.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In 1947, Dantzig also invented the simplex method that, for the first time efficiently, tackled the linear programming problem in most cases.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] When Dantzig arranged a meeting with John von Neumann to discuss his simplex method, von Neumann immediately conjectured the theory of duality by realizing that the problem he had been working in game theory was equivalent.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Dantzig provided formal proof in an unpublished report "A Theorem on Linear Inequalities" on January 5, 1948.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Dantzig's work was made available to public in 1951.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In the post-war years, many industries applied it in their daily planning.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Dantzig's original example was to find the best assignment of 70 people to 70 jobs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The computing power required to test all the permutations to select the best assignment is vast; the number of possible configurations exceeds the number of particles in the observable universe.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] However, it takes only a moment to find the optimum solution by posing the problem as a linear program and applying the simplex algorithm.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The theory behind linear programming drastically reduces the number of possible solutions that must be checked.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The linear programming problem was first shown to be solvable in polynomial time by Leonid Khachiyan in 1979, but a larger theoretical and practical breakthrough in the field came in 1984 when Narendra Karmarkar introduced a new interior-point method for solving linear-programming problems.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Linear programming is a widely used field of optimization for several reasons.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Many practical problems in operations research can be expressed as linear programming problems.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Certain special cases of linear programming, such as *network flow* problems and *multicommodity flow* problems, are considered important enough to have much research on specialized algorithms.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] A number of algorithms for other types of optimization problems work by solving linear programming problems as sub-problems.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Historically, ideas from linear programming have inspired many of the central concepts of optimization theory, such as *duality,* *decomposition,* and the importance of *convexity* and its generalizations.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Likewise, linear programming was heavily used in the early formation of microeconomics, and it is currently utilized in company management, such as planning, production, transportation, and technology.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Although the modern management issues are ever-changing, most companies would like to maximize profits and minimize costs with limited resources.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Google also uses linear programming to stabilize YouTube videos.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Other forms, such as minimization problems, problems with constraints on alternative forms, and problems involving negative variables can always be rewritten into an equivalent problem in standard form.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Suppose that a farmer has a piece of farm land, say *L* hectares, to be planted with either wheat or barley or some combination of the two.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The farmer has *F* kilograms of fertilizer and *P* kilograms of pesticide.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Every hectare of wheat requires *F*1 kilograms of fertilizer and *P*1 kilograms of pesticide, while every hectare of barley requires *F*2 kilograms of fertilizer and *P*2 kilograms of pesticide.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Let S1 be the selling price of wheat and S2 be the selling price of barley, per hectare.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] If we denote the area of land planted with wheat and barley by *x*1 and *x*2 respectively, then profit can be maximized by choosing optimal values for *x*1 and *x*2.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Linear programming problems can be converted into an *augmented form* in order to apply the common form of the simplex algorithm.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This form introduces non-negative *slack variables* to replace inequalities with equalities in the constraints.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] where $\mathbf {s}$ are the newly introduced slack variables, $\mathbf {x}$ are the decision variables, and z is the variable to be maximized.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] where $x_{3},x_{4},x_{5}$ are (non-negative) slack variables, representing in this example the unused area, the amount of unused fertilizer, and the amount of unused pesticide.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Every linear programming problem, referred to as a *primal* problem, can be converted into a dual problem, which provides an upper bound to the optimal value of the primal problem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] There are two ideas fundamental to duality theory.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] One is the fact that (for the symmetric dual) the dual of a dual linear program is the original primal linear program.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Additionally, every feasible solution for a linear program gives a bound on the optimal value of the objective function of its dual.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The weak duality theorem states that the objective function value of the dual at any feasible solution is always greater than or equal to the objective function value of the primal at any feasible solution.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The strong duality theorem states that if the primal has an optimal solution, **x***, then the dual also has an optimal solution, **y***, and **c**T**x***=**b**T**y***.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] A linear program can also be unbounded or infeasible.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Duality theory tells us that if the primal is unbounded then the dual is infeasible by the weak duality theorem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Likewise, if the dual is unbounded, then the primal must be infeasible.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] However, it is possible for both the dual and the primal to be infeasible.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] See dual linear program for details and several more examples.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] such that the matrix *A* and the vectors **b** and **c** are non-negative.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Covering and packing LPs commonly arise as a linear programming relaxation of a combinatorial problem and are important in the study of approximation algorithms.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] For example, the LP relaxations of the set packing problem, the independent set problem, and the matching problem are packing LPs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The LP relaxations of the set cover problem, the vertex cover problem, and the dominating set problem are also covering LPs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Finding a fractional coloring of a graph is another example of a covering LP.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In this case, there is one constraint for each vertex of the graph and one variable for each independent set of the graph.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] It is possible to obtain an optimal solution to the dual when only an optimal solution to the primal is known using the complementary slackness theorem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] So if the *i*-th slack variable of the primal is not zero, then the *i*-th variable of the dual is equal to zero.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Likewise, if the *j*-th slack variable of the dual is not zero, then the *j*-th variable of the primal is equal to zero.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This necessary condition for optimality conveys a fairly simple economic principle.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In standard form (when maximizing), if there is slack in a constrained primal resource (i.e., there are "leftovers"), then additional quantities of that resource must have no value.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Likewise, if there is slack in the dual (shadow) price non-negativity constraint requirement, i.e., the price is not zero, then there must be scarce supplies (no "leftovers").
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Geometrically, the linear constraints define the feasible region, which is a convex polytope.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] A linear function is a convex function, which implies that every local minimum is a global minimum; similarly, a linear function is a concave function, which implies that every local maximum is a global maximum.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] An optimal solution need not exist, for two reasons.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] First, if the constraints are inconsistent, then no feasible solution exists: For instance, the constraints **x** ≥ 2 and **x** ≤ 1 cannot be satisfied jointly; in this case, we say that the LP is *infeasible*.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] However, some problems have distinct optimal solutions; for example, the problem of finding a feasible solution to a system of linear inequalities is a linear programming problem in which the objective function is the zero function (i.e., the constant function taking the value zero everywhere).
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] For this feasibility problem with the zero-function for its objective-function, if there are two distinct solutions, then every convex combination of the solutions is a solution.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The vertices of the polytope are also called *basic feasible solutions*.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The reason for this choice of name is as follows.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Thereby we can study these vertices by means of looking at certain subsets of the set of all constraints (a discrete set), rather than the continuum of LP solutions.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This principle underlies the simplex algorithm for solving linear programs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In many practical problems, "stalling" occurs: many pivots are made with no increase in the objective function.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In rare practical problems, the usual versions of the simplex algorithm may actually "cycle".
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] To avoid cycles, researchers developed new pivoting rules.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In practice, the simplex algorithm is quite efficient and can be guaranteed to find the global optimum if certain precautions against *cycling* are taken.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The simplex algorithm has been proved to solve "random" problems efficiently, i.e. in a cubic number of steps, which is similar to its behavior on practical problems.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] However, the simplex algorithm has poor worst-case behavior: Klee and Minty constructed a family of linear programming problems for which the simplex method takes a number of steps exponential in the problem size.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In fact, for some time it was not known whether the linear programming problem was solvable in polynomial time, i.e. of complexity class P.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Like the simplex algorithm of Dantzig, the criss-cross algorithm is a basis-exchange algorithm that pivots between bases.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] However, the criss-cross algorithm need not maintain feasibility, but can pivot rather from a feasible basis to an infeasible basis.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The criss-cross algorithm does not have polynomial time-complexity for linear programming.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Both algorithms visit all 2*D* corners of a (perturbed) cube in dimension *D*, the Klee–Minty cube, in the worst case.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In contrast to the simplex algorithm, which finds an optimal solution by traversing the edges between vertices on a polyhedral set, interior-point methods move through the interior of the feasible region.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This is the first worst-case polynomial-time algorithm ever found for linear programming.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] To solve a problem which has *n* variables and can be encoded in *L* input bits, this algorithm runs in $O(n^{6}L)$ time.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Leonid Khachiyan solved this long-standing complexity issue in 1979 with the introduction of the ellipsoid method.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The convergence analysis has (real-number) predecessors, notably the iterative methods developed by Naum Z.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Shor and the approximation algorithms by Arkadi Nemirovski and D.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Khachiyan's algorithm was of landmark importance for establishing the polynomial-time solvability of linear programs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The algorithm was not a computational break-through, as the simplex method is more efficient for all but specially constructed families of linear programs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] However, Khachiyan's algorithm inspired new lines of research in linear programming.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Karmarkar proposed a projective method for linear programming.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Karmarkar's algorithm improved on Khachiyan's worst-case polynomial bound (giving $O(n^{3.5}L)$ ).
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Karmarkar claimed that his algorithm was much faster in practical LP than the simplex method, a claim that created great interest in interior-point methods.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Since Karmarkar's discovery, many interior-point methods have been proposed and analyzed.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In 1987, Vaidya proposed an algorithm that runs in $O(n^{3})$ time.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In 1989, Vaidya developed an algorithm that runs in $O(n^{2.5})$ time with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Formally speaking, the algorithm takes $O((n+d)^{1.5}nL)$ arithmetic operations in the worst case, where d is the number of constraints, n is the number of variables, and L is the number of bits.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In 2015, Lee and Sidford showed that linear programming can be solved in ${\tilde {O}}((nnz(A)+d^{2}){\sqrt {d}}L)$ time, where ${\tilde {O}}$ denotes the soft O notation, and $nnz(A)$ represents the number of non-zero elements, and it remains taking $O(n^{2.5}L)$ in the worst case.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In a followup work by Lee, Song and Zhang, they reproduce the same result via a different method.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The current opinion is that the efficiencies of good implementations of simplex-based methods and interior point methods are similar for routine applications of linear programming.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Does linear programming admit a strongly polynomial-time algorithm?
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] There are several open problems in the theory of linear programming, the solution of which would represent fundamental breakthroughs in mathematics and potentially major advances in our ability to solve large-scale linear programs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This closely related set of problems has been cited by Stephen Smale as among the 18 greatest unsolved problems of the 21st century.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The development of such algorithms would be of great theoretical interest, and perhaps allow practical gains in solving large LPs as well.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Although the Hirsch conjecture was recently disproved for higher dimensions, it still leaves the following questions open.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] These questions relate to the performance analysis and development of simplex-like methods.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The immense efficiency of the simplex algorithm in practice despite its exponential-time theoretical performance hints that there may be variations of simplex that run in polynomial or even strongly polynomial time.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] It would be of great practical and theoretical significance to know whether any such variants exist, particularly as an approach to deciding if LP can be solved in strongly polynomial time.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The simplex algorithm and its variants fall in the family of edge-following algorithms, so named because they solve linear programming problems by moving from vertex to vertex along edges of a polytope.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This means that their theoretical performance is limited by the maximum number of edges between any two vertices on the LP polytope.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] As a result, we are interested in knowing the maximum graph-theoretical diameter of polytopal graphs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] It has been proved that all polytopes have subexponential diameter.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] The recent disproof of the Hirsch conjecture is the first step to prove whether any polytope has superpolynomial diameter.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] If any such polytopes exist, then no edge-following variant can run in polynomial time.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Questions about polytope diameter are of independent mathematical interest.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Simplex pivot methods preserve primal (or dual) feasibility.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] On the other hand, criss-cross pivot methods do not preserve (primal or dual) feasibility – they may visit primal feasible, dual feasible or primal-and-dual infeasible bases in any order.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Pivot methods of this type have been studied since the 1970s.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Essentially, these methods attempt to find the shortest pivot path on the arrangement polytope under the linear programming problem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In contrast to polytopal graphs, graphs of arrangement polytopes are known to have small diameter, allowing the possibility of strongly polynomial-time criss-cross pivot algorithm without resolving questions about the diameter of general polytopes.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] If all of the unknown variables are required to be integers, then the problem is called an integer programming (IP) or **integer linear programming** (ILP) problem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] In contrast to linear programming, which can be solved efficiently in the worst case, integer programming problems are in many practical situations (those with bounded variables) NP-hard.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] **0–1 integer programming** or **binary integer programming** (BIP) is the special case of integer programming where variables are required to be 0 or 1 (rather than arbitrary integers).
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] This problem is also classified as NP-hard, and in fact the decision version was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] If only some of the unknown variables are required to be integers, then the problem is called a **mixed integer (linear) programming** (MIP or MILP) problem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] These are generally also NP-hard because they are even more general than ILP programs.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Such integer-programming algorithms are discussed by Padberg and in Beasley.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] A linear program in real variables is said to be ***integral*** if it has at least one optimal solution which is integral, i.e., made of only integer values (*not to be confused with integrals*).
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Likewise, a polyhedron $P=\{x\mid Ax\geq 0\}$ is said to be ***integral*** if for all bounded feasible objective functions *c*, the linear program $\{\max cx\mid x\in P\}$ has an optimum $x^{*}$ with integer coordinates.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] As observed by Edmonds and Giles in 1977, one can equivalently say that the polyhedron P is integral if for every bounded feasible integral objective function *c*, the optimal *value* of the linear program $\{\max cx\mid x\in P\}$ is an integer.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Integral linear programs are of central importance in the polyhedral aspect of combinatorial optimization since they provide an alternate characterization of a problem.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Specifically, for any problem, the convex hull of the solutions is an integral polyhedron; if this polyhedron has a nice/compact description, then we can efficiently find the optimal feasible solution under any linear objective.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Conversely, if we can prove that a linear programming relaxation is integral, then it is the desired description of the convex hull of feasible (integral) solutions.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] One common way of proving that a polyhedron is integral is to show that it is totally unimodular.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] There are other general methods including the integer decomposition property and total dual integrality.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] Other specific well-known integral LPs include the matching polytope, lattice polyhedra, submodular flow polyhedra, and the intersection of two generalized polymatroids/*g*-polymatroids – e.g. see Schrijver 2003.
[src:operations-research/linear-programming] MINTO (Mixed Integer Optimizer, an integer programming solver which uses branch and bound algorithm) has publicly available source code but is not open source.
[src:operations-research/network-flow-problem] The max-flow min-cut theorem equates the value of a maximum flow to the value of a minimum cut, a partition of the vertices of the flow network that minimizes the total capacity of edges crossing from one side of the partition to the other.
[src:operations-research/network-flow-problem] Approximate max-flow min-cut theorems provide an extension of this result to multi-commodity flow problems.
[src:operations-research/network-flow-problem] The Gomory–Hu tree of an undirected flow network provides a concise representation of all minimum cuts between different pairs of terminal vertices.
[src:operations-research/network-flow-problem] Otherwise the problem can be formulated as a more conventional linear program or similar and solved using a general purpose optimization solver.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Employing techniques from other mathematical sciences, such as modeling, statistics, and optimization, operations research arrives at optimal or near-optimal solutions to decision-making problems.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Because of its emphasis on practical applications, operations research has overlapped with many other disciplines, notably industrial engineering.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Operations research is often concerned with determining the extreme values of some real-world objective: the maximum (of profit, performance, or yield) or minimum (of loss, risk, or cost).
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Originating in military efforts before World War II, its techniques have grown to concern problems in a variety of industries.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Nearly all of these techniques involve the construction of mathematical models that attempt to describe the system.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Because of the computational and statistical nature of most of these fields, OR also has strong ties to computer science and analytics.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In the decades after the two World Wars, the tools of operations research were more widely applied to problems in business, industry, and society.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Charles Babbage's research into the cost of transportation and sorting of mail led to England's universal "Penny Post" in 1840, and to studies into the dynamical behaviour of railway vehicles in defence of the GWR's broad gauge.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Beginning in the 20th century, study of inventory management could be considered the origin of modern operations research with economic order quantity developed by Ford W.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Percy Bridgman brought operational research to bear on problems in physics in the 1920s and would later attempt to extend these to the social sciences.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Modern operational research originated at the Bawdsey Research Station in the UK in 1937 as the result of an initiative of the station's superintendent, A.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Rowe conceived the idea as a means to analyse and improve the working of the UK's early-warning radar system, code-named "Chain Home" (CH).
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Initially, Rowe analysed the operating of the radar equipment and its communication networks, expanding later to include the operating personnel's behaviour.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] This revealed unappreciated limitations of the CH network and allowed remedial action to be taken.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Scientists in the United Kingdom (including Patrick Blackett (later Lord Blackett OM PRS), Cecil Gordon, Solly Zuckerman, (later Baron Zuckerman OM, KCB, FRS), C.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Waddington, Owen Wansbrough-Jones, Frank Yates, Jacob Bronowski and Freeman Dyson), and in the United States (George Dantzig) looked for ways to make better decisions in such areas as logistics and training schedules.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The modern field of operational research arose during World War II.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In the World War II era, operational research was defined as "a scientific method of providing executive departments with a quantitative basis for decisions regarding the operations under their control".
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Other names for it included operational analysis (UK Ministry of Defence from 1962) and quantitative management.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] During the Second World War close to 1,000 men and women in Britain were engaged in operational research.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] About 200 operational research scientists worked for the British Army.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Patrick Blackett worked for several different organizations during the war.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In 1941, Blackett moved from the RAE to the Navy, after first working with RAF Coastal Command, in 1941 and then early in 1942 to the Admiralty.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Blackett's team at Coastal Command's Operational Research Section (CC-ORS) included E.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Williams, two future Nobel Prize winners and many other people who went on to be pre-eminent in their fields.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] They undertook a number of crucial analyses that aided the war effort.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Britain introduced the convoy system to reduce shipping losses, but while the principle of using warships to accompany merchant ships was generally accepted, it was unclear whether it was better for convoys to be small or large.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Convoys travel at the speed of the slowest member, so small convoys can travel faster.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] It was also argued that small convoys would be harder for German U-boats to detect.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] On the other hand, large convoys could deploy more warships against an attacker.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Blackett's staff showed that the losses suffered by convoys depended largely on the number of escort vessels present, rather than the size of the convoy.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Their conclusion was that a few large convoys are more defensible than many small ones.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] While performing an analysis of the methods used by RAF Coastal Command to hunt and destroy submarines, one of the analysts asked what colour the aircraft were.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] As most of them were from Bomber Command they were painted black for night-time operations.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] At the suggestion of CC-ORS a test was run to see if that was the best colour to camouflage the aircraft for daytime operations in the grey North Atlantic skies.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Tests showed that aircraft painted white were on average not spotted until they were 20% closer than those painted black.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] This change indicated that 30% more submarines would be attacked and sunk for the same number of sightings.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] As a result of these findings Coastal Command changed their aircraft to using white undersurfaces.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Other work by the CC-ORS indicated that on average if the trigger depth of aerial-delivered depth charges were changed from 100 to 25 feet, the kill ratios would go up.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] It was more efficient to attack those submarines close to the surface when the targets' locations were better known than to attempt their destruction at greater depths when their positions could only be guessed.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Before the change of settings from 100 to 25 feet, 1% of submerged U-boats were sunk and 14% damaged.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] After the change, 7% were sunk and 11% damaged; if submarines were caught on the surface but had time to submerge just before being attacked, the numbers rose to 11% sunk and 15% damaged.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Blackett observed "there can be few cases where such a great operational gain had been obtained by such a small and simple change of tactics".
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Bomber Command's Operational Research Section (BC-ORS), analyzed a report of a survey carried out by RAF Bomber Command.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] For the survey, Bomber Command inspected all bombers returning from bombing raids over Germany over a particular period.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] All damage inflicted by German air defenses was noted and the recommendation was given that armor be added in the most heavily damaged areas.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] This recommendation was not adopted because the fact that the aircraft were able to return with these areas damaged indicated the areas were not vital, and adding armor to non-vital areas where damage is acceptable reduces aircraft performance.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Their suggestion to remove some of the crew so that an aircraft loss would result in fewer personnel losses, was also rejected by RAF command.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Blackett's team made the logical recommendation that the armor be placed in the areas which were completely untouched by damage in the bombers who returned.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] They reasoned that the survey was biased, since it only included aircraft that returned to Britain.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The areas untouched in returning aircraft were probably vital areas, which, if hit, would result in the loss of the aircraft.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Abraham Wald and the Statistical Research Group at Columbia University conducted a similar damage assessment study.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] When Germany organized its air defences into the Kammhuber Line, it was realized by the British that if the RAF bombers were to fly in a bomber stream they could overwhelm the night fighters who flew in individual cells directed to their targets by ground controllers.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] It was then a matter of calculating the statistical loss from collisions against the statistical loss from night fighters to calculate how close the bombers should fly to minimize RAF losses.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The "exchange rate" ratio of output to input was a characteristic feature of operational research.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] By comparing the number of flying hours put in by Allied aircraft to the number of U-boat sightings in a given area, it was possible to redistribute aircraft to more productive patrol areas.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Comparison of exchange rates established "effectiveness ratios" useful in planning.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The ratio of 60 mines laid per ship sunk was common to several campaigns: German mines in British ports, British mines on German routes, and United States mines in Japanese routes.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] On land, the operational research sections of the Army Operational Research Group (AORG) of the Ministry of Supply (MoS) were landed in Normandy in 1944, and they followed British forces in the advance across Europe.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] They analyzed, among other topics, the effectiveness of artillery, aerial bombing and anti-tank shooting.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In 1947, under the auspices of the British Association, a symposium was organized in Dundee.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] With expanded techniques and growing awareness of the field at the close of the war, operational research was no longer limited to only operational, but was extended to encompass equipment procurement, training, logistics and infrastructure.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Operations research also grew in many areas other than the military once scientists learned to apply its principles to the civilian sector.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The development of the simplex algorithm for linear programming was in 1947.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In the 1950s, the term Operations Research was used to describe heterogeneous mathematical methods such as game theory, dynamic programming, linear programming, warehousing, spare parts theory, queue theory, simulation and production control, which were used primarily in civilian industry.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Scientific societies and journals on the subject of operations research were founded in the 1950s, such as the Operation Research Society of America (ORSA) in 1952 and the Institute for Management Science (TIMS) in 1953.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Philip Morse, the head of the Weapons Systems Evaluation Group of the Pentagon, became the first president of ORSA and attracted the companies of the military-industrial complex to ORSA, which soon had more than 500 members.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In the 1960s, ORSA reached 8000 members.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Consulting companies also founded OR groups.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In 1953, Abraham Charnes and William Cooper published the first textbook on Linear Programming.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In the 1950s and 1960s, chairs of operations research were established in the U.S. and United Kingdom (from 1964 in Lancaster) in the management faculties of universities.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Further influences from the U.S. on the development of operations research in Western Europe can be traced here.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The authoritative OR textbooks from the U.S. were published in Germany in German language and in France in French (but not in Italian), such as the book by George Dantzig "Linear Programming"(1963) and the book by C.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] "Introduction to Operations Research"(1957).
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The latter was also published in Spanish in 1973, opening at the same time Latin American readers to Operations Research.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] NATO gave important impulses for the spread of Operations Research in Western Europe; NATO headquarters (SHAPE) organised four conferences on OR in the 1950s—the one in 1956 with 120 participants—bringing OR to mainland Europe.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Within NATO, OR was also known as "Scientific Advisory" (SA) and was grouped together in the Advisory Group of Aeronautical Research and Development (AGARD).
[src:operations-research/operations-research] SHAPE and AGARD organized an OR conference in April 1957 in Paris.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] With the development of computers over the next three decades, operations research can now solve problems with hundreds of thousands of variables and constraints.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Moreover, the large volumes of data required for such problems can now be stored and manipulated very efficiently." Much of operations research (modernly known as 'analytics') relies upon stochastic variables and a therefore access to truly random numbers.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Fortunately, the cybernetics field also required the same level of randomness.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The development of increasingly better random number generators has been a boon to both disciplines.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Modern applications of operations research includes city planning, football strategies, emergency planning, optimizing all facets of industry and economy, and undoubtedly with the likelihood of the inclusion of terrorist attack planning and definitely counterterrorist attack planning.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] More recently, the research approach of operations research, which dates back to the 1950s, has been criticized for being collections of mathematical models but lacking an empirical basis of data collection for applications.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] How to collect data is not presented in the textbooks.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Because of the lack of data, there are also no computer applications in the textbooks.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Operational research is also used extensively in government where evidence-based policy is used.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The field of management science (MS) is known as using operations research models in business.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Stafford Beer characterized this in 1967.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Like operational research itself, management science is an interdisciplinary branch of applied mathematics devoted to optimal decision planning, with strong links with economics, business, engineering, and other sciences.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Management scientists help businesses to achieve their goals using the scientific methods of operational research.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The management scientist's mandate is to use rational, systematic, science-based techniques to inform and improve decisions of all kinds.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Of course, the techniques of management science are not restricted to business applications but may also be applied to military, medical, public administration, charitable, political, or community groups.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Management science is concerned with developing and applying models and concepts that may prove useful in helping to illuminate management issues and solve managerial problems, as well as designing and developing new and better models of organizational excellence.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Applications are abundant such as in airlines, manufacturing companies, service organizations, military branches, and government.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The range of problems and issues to which it has contributed insights and solutions is vast.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Management is also concerned with so-called soft-operational analysis which concerns methods for strategic planning, strategic decision support, problem structuring methods.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In dealing with these sorts of challenges, mathematical modeling and simulation may not be appropriate or may not suffice.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] Therefore, during the past 30 years, a number of non-quantified modeling methods have been developed.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] For the institutionalization of Operations Research, the foundation of IFORS in 1960 was of decisive importance, which stimulated the foundation of national OR societies in Austria, Switzerland and Germany.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] IFORS held important international conferences every three years since 1957.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The constituent members of IFORS form regional groups, such as that in Europe, the Association of European Operational Research Societies (EURO).
[src:operations-research/operations-research] In 2004, the US-based organization INFORMS began an initiative to market the OR profession better, including a website entitled *The Science of Better* which provides an introduction to OR and examples of successful applications of OR to industrial problems.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] This initiative has been adopted by the Operational Research Society in the UK, including a website entitled *Learn About OR*.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] The Institute for Operations Research and the Management Sciences (INFORMS) publishes thirteen scholarly journals about operations research, including the top two journals in their class, according to 2005 Journal Citation Reports.
[src:operations-research/operations-research] These are listed in alphabetical order of their titles.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:operations-research/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
